                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Tanatus</i><br /><br />Basic criteria for mob then flee is weighting mobs current hp vs. your current hp (very possible lvl play some role too) once mob hp drop below your current hp mob flee.<br />One more funny observation - then you FD mob count your HP like it would 100% health. Aka if you got same golem down to 10% but for what ever reason your health below 2000hp golem will chase you but once you FD (assuming that your full healed HP 2500+) golem start flee. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Agreed.  I've seen this when I had a pet up.  Why?  Because the pet becomes highest on the aggro list when you FD... and a full health LoZ pet has what? 4k HP or so?  Obviously, if you didn't have a pet up, the mob will be non-aggro and will insta-heal.<br /><br />So Flee-mode will kick in sooner if the golem is aggro on your pet -- *IF* your pet has more HP than you.  Or in other words, you might be able to get a golem to flee sooner (higher HP %) by FDing.<br /><br /><br />I tested this one time when I got (gasp) trained by a wizzy who got adds on a pull.  <br /><br />It was late in my kite, and Darkness wore off .. and off we ran to the south, pet chasing from behind.  I've been smacked once or twice so my HP is &lt;500 and I'm in low-HP aggro range.  Mob is still in chase mode.  I get to the cliff and FD, expecting the mob to turn and give Jabober a beat down.  But instead, he fled.  So I waited ... Jabober eventually kills him off and I get the exp.  <br /><br />If you kite golems self-buffed ... try it, it works!<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
